<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1437,417,874]" pageId="35" pageNumber="436">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,262,453,478]" pageId="35" pageNumber="436">Note.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bryant" baseAuthorityYear="1943" box="[269,371,454,477]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Amphidraus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="35" pageNumber="436" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="manni">
<emphasis box="[269,371,454,477]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="436">A. manni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bryant" baseAuthorityYear="1943" box="[426,564,453,478]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Amphidraus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="35" pageNumber="436" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mendicus">
<emphasis box="[426,564,453,478]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="436">A. mendicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are clearly members of the euophryines by the spiraled embolus and the well developed 
<collectionCode box="[273,347,489,513]" pageId="35" pageNumber="436">RSDL</collectionCode>
, but differ from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1900" box="[531,668,489,514]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Amphidraus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="35" pageNumber="436" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[531,668,489,514]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="436">Amphidraus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which does not have a well developed 
<collectionCode box="[1115,1189,489,513]" pageId="35" pageNumber="436">RSDL</collectionCode>
, by a simple RTA and an embolic disc poorly developed, with no processes (
<figureCitation box="[754,839,525,550]" captionStart="FIGURE 27" captionStartId="31.[151,250,1919,1941]" captionTargetBox="[207,1382,207,1876]" captionTargetId="figure@31.[184,1408,193,1899]" captionTargetPageId="31" captionText="FIGURE 27. New diagnostic illustrations based on type material. A Truncattus manni (Bryant, 1943) comb. nov., left male palp, ventral view; B same, cHelicera, retrolateral view; C Truncattus mendicus (Bryant, 1943) comb. nov., left male palp, ventral view; D same, cHelicera, retrolateral view; E Titanattus parvus (Mello-Leitão, 1945) comb. nov., epigyne, ventral view. E, embolus; ED, embolic disc; RSDL, retrolateral sperm duct loop; RTA, retrolateral tibial apopHysis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/855527/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="436">Figs 27</figureCitation>
A, 27C). These species share great similarity with the species of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bryant" authorityYear="1943" box="[313,429,561,586]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Antillattus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="35" pageNumber="436" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[313,429,561,586]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="436">Antillattus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-clade, composed of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bryant" authorityYear="1943" box="[666,782,561,586]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Antillattus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="35" pageNumber="436" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[666,782,561,586]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="436">Antillattus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Proszynski &amp; Deeleman-Reinhold, 2012" authorityName="Proszynski &amp; Deeleman-Reinhold" authorityYear="2012" box="[798,1388,561,586]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Petemathis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="35" pageNumber="436" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[798,923,561,586]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="436">Petemathis</emphasis>
Prószyński &amp; Deeleman-Reinhold, 2012
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zhang &amp; Maddison" authorityYear="2012" box="[151,271,598,621]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Truncattus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="35" pageNumber="436" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,271,598,621]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="436">Truncattus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which is restricted to the Caribbean Islands (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Zhang" box="[842,1134,597,622]" pageId="35" pageNumber="436" refString="ZHang, J. X &amp; Maddison, W. P. (2015) Genera of euopHryine jumping spiders (Araneae: Salticidae), witH a combined molecularmorpHological pHylogeny. Zootaxa, 3938 (1), 1 - 147." type="journal article" year="2015">Zhang &amp; Maddison 2015</bibRefCitation>
). The species of this clade usually have two promarginal teeth (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Zhang" box="[621,915,633,658]" pageId="35" pageNumber="436" refString="ZHang, J. X &amp; Maddison, W. P. (2015) Genera of euopHryine jumping spiders (Araneae: Salticidae), witH a combined molecularmorpHological pHylogeny. Zootaxa, 3938 (1), 1 - 147." type="journal article" year="2015">Zhang &amp; Maddison 2015</bibRefCitation>
: figs 58, 65, 66, 73, 75, 88, 94) and a coiled embolus of no more than half a circle (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Zhang" box="[642,933,669,694]" pageId="35" pageNumber="436" refString="ZHang, J. X &amp; Maddison, W. P. (2015) Genera of euopHryine jumping spiders (Araneae: Salticidae), witH a combined molecularmorpHological pHylogeny. Zootaxa, 3938 (1), 1 - 147." type="journal article" year="2015">Zhang &amp; Maddison 2015</bibRefCitation>
: figs 50, 57, 64, 72, 80, 87, 93). Among the genera of this clade, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bryant" baseAuthorityYear="1943" box="[381,482,706,729]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Amphidraus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="35" pageNumber="436" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="manni">
<emphasis box="[381,482,706,729]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="436">A. manni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bryant" baseAuthorityYear="1943" box="[535,672,705,730]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Amphidraus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="35" pageNumber="436" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mendicus">
<emphasis box="[535,672,705,730]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="436">A. mendicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
share more morphological similarities with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zhang &amp; Maddison" authorityYear="2012" box="[1164,1284,706,729]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Truncattus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="35" pageNumber="436" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1164,1284,706,729]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="436">Truncattus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having the chelicera with one bicuspid retromarginal tooth and with a retrolateral depression on the chelicerae (
<figureCitation box="[1264,1350,741,766]" captionStart="FIGURE 27" captionStartId="31.[151,250,1919,1941]" captionTargetBox="[207,1382,207,1876]" captionTargetId="figure@31.[184,1408,193,1899]" captionTargetPageId="31" captionText="FIGURE 27. New diagnostic illustrations based on type material. A Truncattus manni (Bryant, 1943) comb. nov., left male palp, ventral view; B same, cHelicera, retrolateral view; C Truncattus mendicus (Bryant, 1943) comb. nov., left male palp, ventral view; D same, cHelicera, retrolateral view; E Titanattus parvus (Mello-Leitão, 1945) comb. nov., epigyne, ventral view. E, embolus; ED, embolic disc; RSDL, retrolateral sperm duct loop; RTA, retrolateral tibial apopHysis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/855527/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="436">Figs 27</figureCitation>
B, 27D; see 
<bibRefCitation author="Zhang" box="[198,513,777,802]" pageId="35" pageNumber="436" refString="ZHang, J. X. &amp; Maddison, W. P. (2012 b) New euopHryine jumping spiders from tHe Dominican Republic and Puerto Rico (Araneae: Salticidae: EuopHryinae). Zootaxa, 3476, 1 - 54." type="journal article" year="2012" yearSuffix="b">Zhang &amp; Maddison 2012b</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 260; 
<bibRefCitation author="Zhang" box="[641,942,777,802]" pageId="35" pageNumber="436" refString="ZHang, J. X &amp; Maddison, W. P. (2015) Genera of euopHryine jumping spiders (Araneae: Salticidae), witH a combined molecularmorpHological pHylogeny. Zootaxa, 3938 (1), 1 - 147." type="journal article" year="2015">Zhang &amp; Maddison 2015</bibRefCitation>
: Fig. 94), and the male palp with a large proximal tegular lobe (
<figureCitation box="[408,493,813,838]" captionStart="FIGURE 27" captionStartId="31.[151,250,1919,1941]" captionTargetBox="[207,1382,207,1876]" captionTargetId="figure@31.[184,1408,193,1899]" captionTargetPageId="31" captionText="FIGURE 27. New diagnostic illustrations based on type material. A Truncattus manni (Bryant, 1943) comb. nov., left male palp, ventral view; B same, cHelicera, retrolateral view; C Truncattus mendicus (Bryant, 1943) comb. nov., left male palp, ventral view; D same, cHelicera, retrolateral view; E Titanattus parvus (Mello-Leitão, 1945) comb. nov., epigyne, ventral view. E, embolus; ED, embolic disc; RSDL, retrolateral sperm duct loop; RTA, retrolateral tibial apopHysis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/855527/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="436">Figs 27</figureCitation>
A, 27C; see 
<bibRefCitation author="Zhang" box="[632,933,813,838]" pageId="35" pageNumber="436" refString="ZHang, J. X. &amp; Maddison, W. P. (2012 b) New euopHryine jumping spiders from tHe Dominican Republic and Puerto Rico (Araneae: Salticidae: EuopHryinae). Zootaxa, 3476, 1 - 54." type="journal article" year="2012" yearSuffix="b">Zhang &amp; Maddison 2012b</bibRefCitation>
: figs 240, 249, 259). Based on this evidence, these two species are herein transferred to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zhang &amp; Maddison" authorityYear="2012" box="[627,747,850,873]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Truncattus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="35" pageNumber="436" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[627,747,850,873]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="436">Truncattus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
